Q1. What Is a Static Method in Java?

    In Java, when you use the word static before a method, that method becomes a class method. You don’t need to create an object to use it.
    You can call it using the class name. This is very helpful for small methods that don’t use any object-specific data.

    Let’s understand it with a classroom example. Imagine there is a wall clock in the class. Every student can look at the clock,
    and the clock gives the same time to all of them. You don’t need to give every student their own watch.
    The wall clock is like a static method — shared by all, useful to all, and doesn’t belong to anyone.

Standard Definition:
    Static methods are such methods that are associated with a class rather than an object.
    They are declared using the keyword static. We can call static methods without creating an instance of the class.

Q2. Why Are Static Methods Useful?
    Static methods are useful because:
        1. You don’t need to create an object to use them
        2. They save memory and make your code short and clean
        3. They are perfect for utility methods — small pieces of logic that do not depend on any object data
        4. You can reuse them in many places in your program

    In real life, Java already has many static methods that we use every day. For example:
        1. Math.max(a, b) — finds the bigger number
        2. Math.sqrt(a) — finds the square root
        3. Integer.parseInt("123") — changes a string into an integer

    All of these are static methods. You don’t create a Math or Integer object. You just use the method by calling it with the class name. That’s the power of static methods.

Common Interview Questions:

    Q1. Why is the main() method static in Java?
        The main() method is static because it is the starting point of the program. The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) calls the main() method
        before creating any objects. Since there is no object created when the program starts, main() must be static
        so that it can be executed directly using the class name.

    Q2. Can a static method access non-static variables or methods?
        No. A static method cannot directly access non-static (instance) variables or methods.
        This is because non-static members belong to objects, and static methods do not have any object to work with.
        If you want to access non-static members inside a static method, you must first create an object.

    Q3. Can a static method be overridden?
        No. Static methods cannot be overridden in Java because they belong to the class, not to individual objects.
        If you declare a static method with the same name in a subclass, it hides the method from the superclass — but this is known as method hiding, not overriding.

    Q4. Can we call a static method using an object?
        Yes, technically you can call a static method using an object. However, it is not recommended.
        The preferred way is to use the class name to make it clear that the method belongs to the class, not the object.